  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Bichette's Two Homers Power New York Past Atlanta Braves",
    "subheadline": "ATL 5, NYM 7. The long ball carries NYM.",
    "lead_angle": "Bo Bichette crushed a pair of home runs and drove in six runs, powering the New York Mets to a 7-5 victory over the Atlanta Braves at Citi Field. Bichette's second two-run blast in the second inning pushed the Mets’ lead to 4-2, establishing a margin the Braves would chase the rest of the night. Cionel Pérez earned the win in relief, while Spencer Strider took the loss for Atlanta.\n\nThe Mets opened the scoring in the first with a two-run shot from Juan Soto off Strider. Atlanta responded in the second when Ozzie Albies singled home a run and Matt Olson followed with an RBI groundout. But Bichette answered immediately, launching his first two-run homer to restore the Mets’ advantage. He added a solo shot in the fourth, extending New York’s lead to 5-2. The Braves chipped away, with a fifth-inning run and two more in the eighth, but could not close the gap.\n\nBichette’s explosive bat, going 2-for-3 with two round-trippers and six runs batted in, proved instrumental in a tight divisional contest. His power surge was the difference, securing a crucial win for the New York Mets, who now look to gain ground in the National League East standings. Devin Williams closed it out for the save, stifling Atlanta’s late comeback attempt.",
    "reason": "A multi-home-run game by a single player gives the day a clear protagonist."
  },
